{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509124","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509124"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:13:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:13:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11383"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11383"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.05,0.15,0.72,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4028"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76735"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4028","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4028"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11383"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62228"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"238"},{"type":"tags","id":"422"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4495"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6141"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8165"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76735"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman is referred to the respiratory clinic with a one month history of shortness of breath. She is otherwise healthy with no other significant symptoms. She has never smoked and drinks minimal alcohol. There is no exposure to toxins, harmful substances, or sick contacts. She has no allergies, hay fever or eczema. Family history is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer blood pressure is 118/79mmHg, pulse 80/min, temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC, respiratory rate 30/min, SpO2 95% on room air. Chest auscultation shows a loud P2 and bibasal late inspiratory crackles. Her lung function test shows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFEV1: 1.2L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFVC: 1.35L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFEV1:FVC: 0.9 (N: \u0026gt; 0.75 in people aged 40\u201359 years and \u0026gt; 0.70 in people aged 60\u201380 years)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBronchodilator test and gas exchange test are insignificant. The chest CT shows bibasal reticular abnormalities with minimal ground glass opacities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bronchiectasis","Pleural effusion","Sarcoidosis","Pulmonary fibrosis","Bi-lobar pneumonia"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe lung function test results are consistent with a restrictive pattern of lung disease, which rules out \u003Cstrong\u003Ebronchiectasis\u003C/strong\u003E, an obstructive disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPleural effusion\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely given she was previously well, which is not suggestive of an infective aetiology. She did not have chronic organ problems or B symptoms that is suspicious\u00a0 of a malignancy cause, making it unlikely to be a transudative process either.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcoidosis\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely because of an absence of B symptoms, and extra-pulmonary manifestations such as anterior uveitis, arthritis and erythema nodosum.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe shows signs of pulmonary hypertension, which is characteristic of long-standing \u003Cstrong\u003Epulmonary fibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E. Signs of pulmonary hypertension include: reduced pulse oximetry, an elevated JVP, loud P2, a left sided heave consistent with a strong right ventricular impulse, tricuspid regurgitation murmur +/- ascites and lower extremity oedema. The bibasal late inspiratory crackles would be consistent with a fibrosis process. An increased FEV1:FVC suggests a restrictive pattern because their FVC would be reduced and FEV1 may remain normal, whereas a reduced FEV1:FVC suggests an obstructive pattern.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe history is not suggestive of community acquired pneumonia, nor hospital acquired pneumonia. Risk factors such as sick contacts, exposure to high risk areas, alcoholism, smoking, immunocompromised state, being intubated in a hospital, are not present.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The definitive treatment for both cystic fibrosis of the lungs and idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis is lung transplant.","There are many differentials for ground glass opacities including: infectious processes, chronic interstitial diseases, acute alveolar diseases and other causes."],"references":["Spirometry [Internet]. Racgp.org.au. 2022 [cited 2 May 2022]. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/b2aef6c3-a6fb-46bf-9acf-f0215484f04c/Spirometry.aspx","Dunlap B, Weyer G. Pulmonary Hypertension: Diagnosis and Treatment. Am Fam Physician. 2016 Sep 15;94(6):463-9. PMID: 27637122.","Neely ML, Hellkamp AS, Bender S, Todd JL, Liesching T, Luckhardt TR, Oldham JM, Raj R, White ES, Palmer SM. Lung function trajectories in patients with idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis. Respir Res. 2023 Aug 24;24(1):209. doi: 10.1186/s12931-023-02503-5. PMID: 37612608; PMCID: PMC10463468."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62228"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11383"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62228","links":{"self":"https